data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent. The key mappings are:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|-------|-------|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture's `Dispose` |

```csharp
// Fixture class handles one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

// Test class uses constructor/Dispose for per-test setup/teardown
public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key changes:
- **`IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once and shares it across all tests in the class, replacing `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- **Constructor** replaces `[SetUp]` — xUnit creates a new class instance per test.
- **`IDisposable.Dispose`** replaces `[TearDown]`.
- Assertions use `Assert.Equal`/`Assert.NotNull` instead of NUnit's constraint model.

If your setup/teardown is `async`, implement `IAsyncLifetime` (with `InitializeAsync`/`DisposeAsync`) instead of using the constructor and `IDisposable`.
